    "narrative": "Ghost Ride the WHIP enters today with a balanced offensive outlook, led by three high-ceiling plays. **Vinnie Pasquantino** (72.92) is our strongest start against Civale, bolstered by a 10% park factor and a significant 14% platoon edge. Joining him at the top are **Corbin Carroll** (66.51) and **Seiya Suzuki** (66.21); while **Corbin Carroll** faces a high-efficiency holding pitcher, his elite xwOBA metrics keep him locked in. **Seiya Suzuki** benefits immensely from a 19% SP skill boost against Buehler, compensating for the uncertainty of a pending lineup. **James Wood** (64.84) remains a primary catalyst today; despite facing a capable holder in Holmes, his leadoff position provides a 10% efficiency bump that cements his place in the lineup.\n\nOur most difficult bench decision involved **Josh Naylor** (53.45). He was the clear \"next man up\" but fell just shy of the threshold due to a brutal matchup against the arm of Ryan, which slashed his base projection by 16%. We prioritize our stolen base specialists in this Roto format, and even with the efficiency drain against elite pitchers like deGrom, we are opting to keep **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** in the UTIL slot to capture any potential baserunning upside. **Mickey Moniak** (57.59) warrants a close watch; he carries an impressive efficiency score despite a 19% downgrade from facing Ch. Burns, as his presence in the #2 hole and a strong platoon advantage keep him ahead of the remaining bench assets like **Alex Freeland** and **Luis Campusano**, the latter of whom was benched for falling below our 40-point floor.\n\nRisk management remains a priority given the \"Lineup Pending\" tags for **Dalton Rushing** and **Seiya Suzuki**. While **Seiya Suzuki** has the data to survive a slight lineup drop, **Dalton Rushing** (51.60) is operating near the lower end of our starting comfort zone; his value is strictly tied to his assumed #7 spot. We are also wary of **Jazz Chisholm Jr.** facing deGrom; while he is 